Definition 5.7. For category $\mathcal{C}$ we define the category $\mathcal{C}_{S}$ as having: • Objects: The same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ • Morphisms: We define $\mathcal{C}_{S}(A,B)=S(\mathcal{C}(A,B))$ Composition is given as follows: $\sum_{j}q_{j}|g_{j}\rangle\circ\sum_{i}p_{i}|f_{i}\rangle=\sum_{i,j}p_{i}q_{j}% |g_{j}\circ f_{i}\rangle$
Definition 4.9. For category $\mathcal{C}$ we define the category $\mathcal{C}_{P_{\omega}}$ as having: • Objects: The same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ • Morphisms: We define $\mathcal{C}_{P_{\omega}}(A,B)=P_{\omega}(\mathcal{C}(A,B))$ We define composition as follows: $V\circ U=\{v\circ u\mid v\in V,u\in U\}$ Identities are then given by the singletons containing the identities from $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a $\otimes$-triangulated category and let $A$ be an algebra object. An object of $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be $A$-nilpotent if it belongs to the thick $\otimes$-ideal generated by $A$. The algebra $A$ is said to be descendable if the unit of $\mathcal{C}$ is $A$-nilpotent. We will say that a map $R\to R^{\prime}$ of $\mathbb{E}_{\infty}$-ring spectra is descendable if $R^{\prime}$ is descendable in $\mathrm{Mod}(R)$, the category of $R$-module spectra.
Definition 2.1. A thick subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ is a full subcategory $\mathcal{D}\subset\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the following three conditions: (1) $0\in\mathcal{D}$. (2) If $X_{1}\to X_{2}\to X_{3}$ is a cofiber sequence (i.e., exact triangle) in $\mathcal{C}$, and two out of three of the $\left\{X_{i}\right\}$ belong to $\mathcal{D}$, then the third belongs to $\mathcal{D}$. (3) $\mathcal{D}$ is idempotent-complete. Equivalently, if $X,Y\in\mathcal{C}$ and $X\oplus Y\in\mathcal{D}$, we have $X,Y\in\mathcal{D}$. Given a collection $\mathcal{S}\subset\mathcal{C}$ of objects, there is a smallest thick subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ containing $\mathcal{S}$; we will write $\mathrm{Thick}(\mathcal{S})$ for this and call it the thick subcategory generated by $\mathcal{S}$.
Definition 7.7. For $\mu\in\mathds{k}$ and $(i,j,k,\iota)\in\Lambda^{6}$. Let $\Lambda^{6}(\mu)$ be the algebra generated by $x$, $y$, $a$, $b$, $c$, $d$ satisfying the relations $\displaystyle a^{4}=1,\quad b^{2}=0,\quad c^{2}=0,\quad d^{4}=1,\quad a^{2}d^{% 2}=1,\quad ad=da,\quad bc=0=cb,$ $\displaystyle ab=\xi ba,\quad ac=\xi ca,\quad bd=\xi db,\quad cd=\xi dc,\quad bd% =ca,\quad ba=cd,$ $\displaystyle ax=-\xi xa,\quad bx=-\xi xb,\quad cx=\lambda_{1}xc,\quad dx=% \lambda_{1}xd,$ $\displaystyle ay+ya=\lambda_{4}xc,\quad by+yb=\lambda_{4}xd,\quad cy+\lambda_{% 4}yc=xa,\quad dy+\lambda_{4}yd=xb,$ $\displaystyle x^{2}+2\lambda_{4}y^{2}=\mu(1-a^{2}),\quad xy+\lambda_{4}yx=% \lambda_{4}\mu ca,\quad x^{4}=0,$ the coalgebra structure is given by $\displaystyle\Delta(a)$ $\displaystyle=a\otimes a+b\otimes c,\quad\Delta(b)=a\otimes b+b\otimes d,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(c)$ $\displaystyle=c\otimes a+d\otimes c,\quad\Delta(d)=d\otimes d+c\otimes b,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(x)$ $\displaystyle=x\otimes 1+da^{j-1}\otimes x+(\lambda_{2}\lambda_{4}-1)ca^{j-1}% \otimes y,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(y)$ $\displaystyle=y\otimes 1+a^{j}\otimes y-\frac{1}{2}(\lambda_{2}\lambda_{4}+1)% ba^{j-1}\otimes x.$
Definition 3.1. $\displaystyle\mathcal{A}:=\langle g,h,x\mid g^{4}=1,h^{2}=1,hg=gh,hx=-xh,gx=xg% ,x^{2}=1-g^{2}\rangle.$ $\displaystyle\Delta(g)=g\otimes g,\quad\Delta(h)=h\otimes h,\quad\Delta(x)=x% \otimes 1+gh\otimes x.$
Definition 7.5. For $\mu\in\mathds{k}$ and $(i,j,k,\iota)\in\Lambda^{5}$, Let $\Lambda^{5}(\mu)$ be the algebra generated by $x$, $y$, $a$, $b$, $c$, $d$ satisfying the relations $\displaystyle a^{4}=1,\quad b^{2}=0,\quad c^{2}=0,\quad d^{4}=1,\quad a^{2}d^{% 2}=1,\quad ad=da,\quad bc=0=cb,$ $\displaystyle ab=\xi ba,\quad ac=\xi ca,\quad bd=\xi db,\quad cd=\xi dc,\quad bd% =ca,\quad ba=cd.$ $\displaystyle ax=-\lambda_{4}\xi xa,\quad bx=-\lambda_{4}\xi xb,\quad cx=\xi xc% ,\quad dx=\xi xd,$ $\displaystyle ay+\lambda_{4}ya=\lambda_{4}xc,\quad by+\lambda_{4}yb=\lambda_{4% }xd,\quad cy+yc=xa,\quad dy+yd=xb,$ $\displaystyle x^{2}+2\lambda_{4}y^{2}=\mu(1-a^{2}),\quad xy+\lambda_{4}yx=% \frac{1}{2}(\lambda_{4}-\lambda_{2})(\lambda_{2}+1)\mu ca,\quad x^{4}=0,$ the coalgebra structure is given by $\displaystyle\Delta(a)$ $\displaystyle=a\otimes a+b\otimes c,\quad\Delta(b)=a\otimes b+b\otimes d,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(c)$ $\displaystyle=c\otimes a+d\otimes c,\quad\Delta(d)=d\otimes d+c\otimes b,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(x)$ $\displaystyle=x\otimes 1+a^{j}\otimes x-(\lambda_{2}+\lambda_{4})ba^{j-1}% \otimes y,$ $\displaystyle\Delta(y)$ $\displaystyle=y\otimes 1+da^{j-1}\otimes y+\frac{1}{2}\xi(\lambda_{2}-\lambda_% {4})ca^{j-1}\otimes x.$
Definition 2.8. Let $M$ be a Yetter-Drinfeld module over $H$ and $\sigma$ is a Hopf $2$-cocycle of $H$. Then there is a corresponding Yetter-Drinfeld module over $H^{\sigma}$ denoted by $M^{\sigma}$ defined as: it is $M$ as a comodule, and the $H^{\sigma}$-action is given by $\displaystyle a\cdot^{\sigma}m=\sum\sigma((a_{(2)}\cdot m_{(0)})_{(1)},a_{(1)}% )(a_{(2)}\cdot m_{(0)})_{(0)}\sigma^{-1}(a_{(3)}\otimes m_{(1)}),$
Definition 2.1. Let $H$ be a Hopf algebra with bijective antipode. A Yetter-Drinfeld module over $H$ is a left $H$-module and a left $H$-comodule with comodule structure denoted by $\delta:V\mapsto H\otimes V,v\mapsto v_{(-1)}\otimes v_{(0)}$, such that $\displaystyle\delta(h\cdot v)=h_{(1)}v_{(-1)}S(h_{(3)})\otimes h_{(2)}v_{(0)},$ for all $v\in V,h\in H$. Let ${}^{H}_{H}\mathcal{YD}$ be the category of Yetter-Drinfeld modules over $H$ with $H$-linear and $H$-colinear maps as morphisms.
Definition 2.6. Let $H$ be a finite-dimensional Hopf algebra with bijective antipode $S$ over $\mathds{k}$. The Drinfeld double $\mathcal{D}(H)=H^{\ast\,cop}\otimes H$ is a Hopf algebra with the tensor product coalgebra structure and algebra structure defined by $\displaystyle(p\otimes a)(q\otimes b)=p\langle q_{(3)},a_{(1)}\rangle q_{(2)}% \otimes a_{(2)}\langle q_{(1)},S^{-1}(a_{(3)})\rangle.$
Definition 2.3. Let $V\in{}^{H}_{H}\mathcal{YD}$ and $I(V)\subset T(V)$ be the largest $\mathds{N}$-graded ideal and coideal such that $I(V)\cap V=0$. We call $\mathcal{B}(V)=T(V)/I(V)$ the Nichols algebra of $V$. Then $\mathcal{B}(V)=\oplus_{n\geq 0}\mathcal{(}B)^{n}(V)$ is an $\mathds{N}$-graded Hopf algebra in ${}^{H}_{H}\mathcal{YD}$.
Definition 2.4. In (1)-(6) we follow the terminology of [17]. (1) A subset $D\subseteq X$ of a partially ordered set $X$ is called directed whenever $D\neq\varnothing$ and, for all $x,y\in D$, there is some $z\in D$ with $x\leq z$ and $y\leq z$. We are going to use the notation $\bigvee^{\uparrow}D$ to express the supremum of a set $D$ and, at the same time, indicate that $D$ is directed. (2) The way below relation $\ll$ is defined as follows: $x\ll y$ provided that, for every directed subset $D\subseteq X$, if $y\leq\bigvee^{\uparrow}D$, then $x\leq d$ for some $d\in D$. An element $x\in X$ is called compact whenever $x\ll x$. (3) The totally below relation $\lll$ is defined in a similar way: $x\lll y$ whenever, for every subset $S\subseteq X$, if $y\leq\bigvee S$, then $x\leq d$ for some $d\in S$. An element $x\in X$ is called totally compact whenever $x\lll x$. (4) A partially ordered set $X$ is called directed complete whenever every directed subset of $X$ has a supremum. Furthermore, $X$ is said to be bounded complete if every subset with an upper bound has a least one; equivalently, it has all non-empty infima. (5) A partially ordered set $X$ is continuous if each one of its elements $x$ is the directed supremum of all elements $y$ with $y\ll x$. A domain is a continuous poset with directed suprema. Furthermore, a complete partially ordered set $X$ is called completely distributive whenever every $x\in X$ is the supremum of all elements $y$ with $y\lll x$. (6) A domain $X$ with each $x\in X$ satisfying the equality $x=\bigvee^{\uparrow}\{y\in X\mid y\leq x,\,y\ll y\}$ is an algebraic domain. The designation of continuous lattice [30] is used for a domain which is also a lattice; hence, a continuous lattice is a complete and continuous partially ordered set. Analogously, an algebraic lattice is an algebraic domain which is also a lattice. A completely distributive partially ordered set where $x=\bigvee\{y\in X\mid y\leq x,\,y\lll y\}$, for every $x\in X$, is called totally algebraic. (7) A topological space $X$ is called stably compact whenever $X$ is sober, locally compact and every finite intersection of compact saturated subsets is compact (see [19]). A continuous map $f:X\to Y$ between stably compact spaces is called spectral whenever $f^{-1}(K)$ is compact, for every compact saturated subset $K\subseteq Y$. We denote by $\mathsf{StablyComp}$ the category of stably compact spaces and spectral maps. A stably compact space $X$ is called spectral whenever the compact open subsets form a basis for the topology of $X$; equivalently, if the cone $(f:X\to\mathrm{S})_{f}$ of all spectral maps into the the Sierpiński space is initial with respect to the forgetful functor $\mathsf{Top}\to\mathsf{Set}$; and this in turn is equivalent to $(f:X\to\mathrm{S})_{f}$ being initial with respect to the canonical forgetful functor $\mathsf{StablyComp}\to\mathsf{Set}$. It is also well-known that a continuous map $f:X\to Y$ between spectral spaces is spectral if and only if $f^{-1}(K)$ is compact, for every compact open subset $K\subseteq Y$. The full subcategory of $\mathsf{StablyComp}$ defined by all spectral spaces we denote by $\mathsf{Spec}$; it is a reflective subcategory since by definition it is closed under initial cones (see [3, Theorem 16.8]). Finally, we note that $\mathsf{StablyComp}$ is equivalent to the category of Nachbin’s partially ordered compact Hausdorff spaces and monotone continuous maps. Here a stably compact space $X$ corresponds to the partially ordered compact Hausdorff space with the same underlying set, the order relation is the specialisation order, and the compact Hausdorff topology is given by the so-called patch topology (see [25, 19] for details).
Definition 3.1. An object $Y$ in $\mathsf{X}$ is called Cauchy complete whenever every left adjoint morphism $r:X\mathrel{\mathmakebox[\widthof{$\xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}$}]{% \xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}\hskip-12.04pt{\circ}\hskip 4.3pt}}Y$ in $\mathsf{X}_{\mathbbm{T}}$ is of the form $r=f_{*}$, for some $f:X\to Y$ in $\mathsf{X}$.
Definition 3.11. A morphism $f:X\to Y$ in $\mathsf{X}$ is called $\mathbbm{T}$-dense whenever $f_{*}:X\mathrel{\mathmakebox[\widthof{$\xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}$}]{% \xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}\hskip-12.04pt{\circ}\hskip 4.3pt}}Y$ has a right adjoint $f^{*}:Y\mathrel{\mathmakebox[\widthof{$\xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}$}]{% \xrightarrow{\rule{6.235pt}{0.0pt}}\hskip-12.04pt{\circ}\hskip 4.3pt}}X$ in $\mathsf{X}_{\mathbbm{T}}$.
Definition 2.1. A monad $\mathbbm{T}=(T,m,e)$ on an order-enriched category $\mathsf{X}$ is called order-enriched whenever $T:\mathsf{X}\to\mathsf{X}$ is so. An order-enriched monad $\mathbbm{T}=(T,m,e)$ is of Kock-Zöberlein type whenever $Te_{X}\leq e_{TX}$, for all object $X$ in $\mathsf{X}$.
Definition 4.4. Let $\mathsf{A}$ be an order-enriched category with weighted limits. An object $S$ of $\mathsf{A}$ is said to be a regular cogenerator if the the diagram (4.iv) is an equaliser.
Definition 3.5. A $\mathbbm{T}$-algebra $X$ is called split whenever the left adjoint $\alpha:TX\to X$ of $e_{X}:X\to TX$ has a left adjoint $t:X\to TX$ in $\mathsf{X}$; and $X$ is called algebraic whenever $X$ is isomorphic to a free algebra in $\mathsf{X}^{\mathbbm{T}}$.
Definition 27. A probability measure $(\alpha,\mu)$ on $X^{\omega}$ is exchangeable if for all permutations $\pi$ on positive integers, $[\alpha,\mu]=[\alpha_{\pi},\mu]\text{,}$ where $\alpha_{\pi}(r)_{i}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\textup{def}}}{{=}}\alpha(r)_{\pi(i)}$ for all $r\in\mathbb{R}$ and $i\geq 1$.
Definition 11. A morphism of quasi-Borel spaces $(X,M_{X})\to(Y,M_{Y})$ is a function $f\colon X\to Y$ such that $f\circ\alpha\in M_{Y}$ if $\alpha\in M_{X}$. Write $\mathbf{QBS}\big{(}(X,M_{X}),(Y,M_{Y})\big{)}$ for the set of morphisms from $(X,M_{X})$ to $(Y,M_{Y})$.
Definition 7. A quasi-Borel space is a set $X$ together with a set $M_{X}\subseteq[\mathbb{R}\to X]$ satisfying: • $\alpha\circ f\in M_{X}$ if $\alpha\in M_{X}$ and $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ is measurable; • $\alpha\in M_{X}$ if $\alpha\colon\mathbb{R}\to X$ is constant; • if ${\mathbb{R}=\biguplus_{i\in\mathbb{N}}S_{i}}$, with each set $S_{i}$ Borel, and ${\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\ldots\in M_{X}}$, then ${\beta}$ is in ${M_{X}}$, where ${\beta(r)=\alpha_{i}(r)}$ for $r\in S_{i}$.
Definition 19. Let $(X,\Sigma_{X})$ and $(Y,\Sigma_{Y})$ be measurable spaces. A probability kernel from $X$ to $Y$ is a function $k:X\times\Sigma_{Y}\to[0,1]$ such that $k(x,-)$ is a probability measure for all $x\in X$ (Def. 3), and $k(-,U)$ is a measurable function for all $U\in\Sigma_{Y}$ (Def. 4).
Definition 1. The Borel sets form the family $\Sigma_{\mathbb{R}}$ of subsets of $\mathbb{R}$ inductively defined as follows: • intervals $(a,b)$ are Borel sets; • complements of Borel sets are Borel; • countable unions of Borel sets are Borel.
Definition 2. A probability measure on $\mathbb{R}$ is a function $\mu\colon\Sigma_{\mathbb{R}}\to[0,1]$ satisfying $\mu(\mathbb{R})=1$ and $\mu(\biguplus S_{i})=\sum\mu(S_{i})$ for any countable sequence of disjoint Borel sets $S_{i}$.
Definition 4. Let $(X,\Sigma_{X})$ and $(Y,\Sigma_{Y})$ be measurable spaces. A measurable function $f\colon X\to Y$ is a function such that ${f}^{\textup{-1}}(U)\in\Sigma_{X}$ when $U\in\Sigma_{Y}$.
Definition 3. A $\sigma$-algebra on a set $X$ is a nonempty family of subsets of $X$ that is closed under complements and countable unions. A measurable space is a pair $(X,\Sigma_{X})$ of a set $X$ and a $\sigma$-algebra $\Sigma_{X}$ on it. A probability measure on a measurable space $X$ is a function $\mu\colon\Sigma_{X}\to[0,1]$ satisfying $\mu(X)=1$ and $\mu(\biguplus S_{i})=\sum\mu(S_{i})$ for any countable sequence of disjoint sets $S_{i}\in\Sigma_{X}$.
Definition 10. A probability measure on a quasi-Borel space $(X,M_{X})$ is a pair $(\alpha,\mu)$ of $\alpha\in M_{X}$ and a probability measure $\mu$ on $\mathbb{R}$ (as in Def. 2).
Definition 6.6. In a braided category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,\mathbf{I},c),$ a right module structure $\rho:M\otimes H\rightarrow M$ and a right comodule structure $\delta:M\rightarrow M\otimes H$ on $M\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C})$ are said to form a (right-right) Hopf module structure over $H\in\mathbf{Bialg}(\mathcal{C})$ if they satisfy the Hopf compatibility condition $\delta\circ\rho=(\rho\otimes\mu)\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{M}\otimes c_{H,H}% \otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ(\delta\otimes\Delta):M\otimes H\rightarrow M% \otimes H.$ The category of right-right Hopf modules over $H$ and their morphisms is denoted by $\mathbf{Mod}_{H}^{H}.$
Definition 3.10. The (bi)differentials from the above theorem and corollary are called multi-braided.
Definition 4.4. ➺ Given a $V\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C}),$ a morphism pair $(\eta:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow V,\epsilon:V\rightarrow\mathbf{I})$ is called normalized if $\epsilon\circ\eta=\operatorname{Id}_{\mathbf{I}}.$ ➺ Given $V,W\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C}),$ a morphism $\xi:V\otimes W\rightarrow W\otimes V$ is called natural with respect to a morphism $\varphi:V^{n}\rightarrow V^{m}$ (or $\psi:W^{n}\rightarrow W^{m}$) if $\xi^{1}\circ\cdots\circ\xi^{m}\circ(\varphi\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{W})=(% \operatorname{Id}_{W}\otimes\varphi)\circ\xi^{1}\circ\cdots\circ\xi^{n},$ or, respectively, $\xi^{m}\circ\cdots\circ\xi^{1}\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{V}\otimes\psi)=(\psi% \otimes\operatorname{Id}_{V})\circ\xi^{n}\circ\cdots\circ\xi^{1}.$ In the case $V=W$ both conditions are required.
Definition 3.1. The permutation sets $Sh_{p,q}:=\bigg{\{}\theta\in S_{p+q}\;\begin{array}[]{|l}\theta(1)<\theta(2)<% \ldots<\theta(p),\\ \theta(p+1)<\theta(p+2)<\ldots<\theta(p+q)\end{array}\bigg{\}}$ or, more generally, $Sh_{p_{1},p_{2},\ldots,p_{k}}:=\Bigg{\{}\theta\in S_{p_{1}+p_{2}+\cdots+p_{k}}% \;\begin{array}[]{|l}\theta(1)<\theta(2)<\ldots<\theta(p_{1}),\\ \theta(p_{1}+1)<\ldots<\theta(p_{1}+p_{2}),\\ \ldots,\\ \theta(p+1)<\ldots<\theta(p+p_{k})\end{array}\Bigg{\}}$ where $p=p_{1}+p_{2}+\cdots+p_{k-1},$ are called shuffle sets.
Definition 3.14. The multi-braided modules from the above proposition are called adjoint.
Definition 5.1. ➺ A bialgebra structure in a braided category $(\mathcal{C},\otimes,\mathbf{I},c)$ is a UAA structure $(\mu,\nu)$ and a counital coassociative coalgebra (= coUAA) structure $(\Delta,\varepsilon)$ on an object $H,$ compatible in the following sense: $\displaystyle\Delta\circ\mu$ $\displaystyle=(\mu\otimes\mu)\circ c_{2}\circ(\Delta\otimes\Delta),$ $\displaystyle\Delta\circ\nu$ $\displaystyle=\nu\otimes\nu,$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon\circ\mu$ $\displaystyle=\varepsilon\otimes\varepsilon,$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon\circ\nu$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{Id}_{\mathbf{I}}.$ The category of bialgebras and bialgebra morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ is denoted by $\mathbf{Bialg}(\mathcal{C}).$ ➺ $H$ is a Hopf algebra in $\mathcal{C}$ if moreover it has an antipode, i.e. an endomorphism $s$ of $H$ satisfying $\mu\circ(s\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{H})\circ\Delta=\mu\circ(\operatorname{Id}_% {H}\otimes s)\circ\Delta=\nu\circ\varepsilon.$ The category of Hopf algebras and their morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ is denoted by $\mathbf{HAlg}(\mathcal{C}).$ ➺ For a bialgebra $H$ in $\mathcal{C},$ a left $H$-module algebra is a UAA $(M,\mu_{M},\nu_{M})$ endowed with a left $H$-module structure $\lambda:H\otimes M\rightarrow M,$ such that $\mu_{M}$ and $\nu_{M}$ are $H$-module morphisms: $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\mu_{M})$ $\displaystyle=\mu_{M}\circ(\lambda\otimes\lambda)\circ c_{2}\circ(\Delta% \otimes\operatorname{Id}_{M}^{\otimes 2}),$ $\displaystyle\lambda\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{H}\otimes\nu_{M})$ $\displaystyle=\nu_{M}\circ\varepsilon.$ Right $H$-module algebras, $H$-comodule algebras and $H$-bi(co)module algebras are defined similarly. The categories of module algebras and their morphisms are denoted by ${}_{H}\!\mathbf{ModAlg},$ $\mathbf{ModAlg}_{H},$ ${}^{H}\!\mathbf{ModAlg}$ etc.
Definition 3.5. Take $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C}).$ ➺ The family of morphisms $\underset{\overline{\sigma}}{\shuffle}{}_{p,q}:=\sum_{\theta\in Sh_{p,q}}(T_{% \theta})^{\overline{\sigma}}:{T(\overline{V})_{p}^{\leftarrow}}\otimes T(% \overline{V})_{q}^{\leftarrow}\rightarrow T(\overline{V})_{p+q}^{\leftarrow},$ where for given reversely ordered tensor products $W$ in $T(\overline{V})_{p}^{\leftarrow}$ and $U$ in $T(\overline{V})_{q}^{\leftarrow}$ the summation runs only over $\theta$ for which the action $(T_{\theta})^{\overline{\sigma}}$ is defined on $W\otimes U$ and takes values in the $T(\overline{V})_{p+q}^{\leftarrow}$ part of $V^{p+q},$ is called the multi-quantum shuffle multiplication. ➺ The family of morphisms $\underset{\overline{\sigma}}{\cshuffle}{}_{p,q}:=\sum_{\theta\in Sh_{p,q}}(T_{% \theta^{-1}})^{\overline{\sigma}}:T(\overline{V})_{p+q}^{\rightarrow}% \rightarrow T(\overline{V})_{p}^{\rightarrow}\otimes T(\overline{V})_{q}^{\rightarrow}$ is called the multi-quantum coshuffle comultiplication. ➺ More generally, replacing $Sh_{p,q}$ by $Sh_{p_{1},\ldots,p_{k}},$ one gets morphisms $\underset{\overline{\sigma}}{\shuffle}{}_{p_{1},\ldots,p_{k}}$ and $\underset{\overline{\sigma}}{\cshuffle}{}_{p_{1},\ldots,p_{k}}.$
Definition 2.4. ➺ A right multi-braided module over $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ is an object $M$ equipped with morphisms $\overline{\rho}:=(\rho_{i}:M\otimes V_{i}\rightarrow M)_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r}$ satisfying $\rho_{j}\circ(\rho_{i}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{j})=\rho_{i}\circ(\rho_{j}% \otimes\operatorname{Id}_{i})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{M}\otimes\sigma_{i,j}):M% \otimes V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\rightarrow M\qquad\forall\,1\leqslant i\leqslant j\leqslant r$ or, graphically, $\rho_{j}$$\rho_{i}$$j$$i$$M$$=$$\rho_{i}$$\rho_{j}$$j$$i$$M$$\sigma_{i,j}$. ➺ Left multi-braided modules and left/right multi-braided comodules, as well as multi-braided (co)module morphisms, are defined in the usual way. ➺ The category of right multi-braided modules and their morphisms is denoted by $\mathbf{Mod}_{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}.$ We use notation ${}_{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}\!\mathbf{Mod}$ in the left case and $\mathbf{Mod}^{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}$ and ${}^{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})}\!\mathbf{Mod}$ in the co-cases. ➺ We talk about braided (co)modules in the rank $1$ case.
Definition 2.1. ➺ A braided system in $\mathcal{C}$ is an ordered finite family $V_{1},V_{2},\ldots,V_{r}\in\operatorname{Ob}(\mathcal{C})$ endowed with a braiding, i.e. morphisms $\sigma_{i,j}:V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\rightarrow V_{j}\otimes V_{i}$ $\forall\quad 1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j}\leqslant r$ satisfying the (colored) Yang-Baxter equation (=YBE) $(\sigma_{j,k}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{â¯i})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{â¯j}% \otimes\sigma_{i,k})\circ(\sigma_{i,j}\otimes\operatorname{Id}_{k})=(% \operatorname{Id}_{k}\otimes\sigma_{i,j})\circ(\sigma_{i,k}\otimes% \operatorname{Id}_{j})\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{i}\otimes\sigma_{j,k})$ on all the tensor products $V_{i}\otimes V_{j}\otimes V_{k}$ with $1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j\leqslant k}\leqslant r.$ Such a system is denoted by $((V_{i})_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r};(\sigma_{i,j})_{1\leqslant i\leqslant j% \leqslant r})$ or briefly $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma}).$ ➺ The rank of a braided system is the number $r$ of its components. ➺ A braided morphism $\overline{f}:(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\rightarrow(\overline{W},% \overline{\xi})$ between two braided systems in $\mathcal{C}$ of the same rank $r$ is a collection of morphisms $(f_{i}\in\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(V_{i},W_{i}))_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r}$ respecting the braiding, i.e. $(f_{j}\otimes f_{i})\circ\sigma_{i,j}=\xi_{i,j}\circ(f_{i}\otimes f_{j})\quad% \forall\;1\leqslant\underline{i\leqslant j}\leqslant r.$ ➺ The category of rank $r$ braided systems and braided morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$ is denoted by $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C}),$ or $\mathbf{Br}(\mathcal{C})$ in the rank one case. ➺ Rank $1$ braided systems are called braided objects in $\mathcal{C}.$ ➺ For given $1\leqslant s\leqslant t\leqslant r,$ the braided $(s,t)$-subsystem of $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma}),$ denoted by $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})[s,t],$ is the subfamily $V_{s},\ldots,V_{t}$ with the corresponding components $\sigma_{i,j}$ of $\overline{\sigma}.$
Definition 4.6. A braided system of the type described in the above theorem is called a braided system of UAAs, and the UAA $\overleftarrow{V}$ is called the multi-braided tensor product of the UAAs $V_{1},\ldots,V_{r},$ denoted (abusively) by $\overleftarrow{V}=V_{r}\underset{\xi}{\otimes}V_{r-1}\underset{\xi}{\otimes}% \cdots\underset{\xi}{\otimes}V_{1}.$
Definition 3.3. ➺ An ordered tensor product for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ is a tensor product of the form $V_{1}^{\otimes m_{1}}\otimes V_{2}^{\otimes m_{2}}\otimes\cdots\otimes V_{r}^{% \otimes m_{r}},\qquad m_{i}\geqslant 0.$ ➺ A reversely ordered tensor product is one of the form $V_{r}^{\otimes m_{r}}\otimes V_{r-1}^{\otimes m_{r-1}}\otimes\cdots\otimes V_{% 1}^{\otimes m_{1}},\qquad m_{i}\geqslant 0.$ ➺ The degree of such a tensor product is simply the sum $\sum_{i=1}^{r}m_{i}.$ ➺ The direct sum of the (reversely) ordered tensor products of degree $n$ is denoted by $T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}$ (respectively, $T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\leftarrow}$).
Definition 6.5. ➺ Given a monoidal category $\mathcal{C},$ denote by $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}{}^{\bullet}_{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ the category of ✓ $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma},\overline{\nu})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}^{\bullet% }(\mathcal{C})$ endowed with distinguished morphisms $\overline{\varepsilon}:=(\varepsilon_{i}:V_{i}\rightarrow\mathbf{I})_{1% \leqslant i\leqslant r}$ called counits, such that $(\nu_{i},\varepsilon_{i})$ is a normalized pair for each $i,$ and ✓ morphisms from $\mathbf{BrSyst}^{\bullet}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ preserving moreover all the counits. Objects $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma},\overline{\nu},\overline{\varepsilon})$ of $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}{}^{\bullet}_{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ are called rank $r$ bipointed braided systems. ➺ The groupoid of rank $r$ bipointed braided systems and their isomorphisms is denoted by ${}^{*}\!\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}{}^{\bullet}_{\bullet}(\mathcal{C}).$ ➺ In the rank $1$ case, notations $\mathbf{Br}^{\bullet}_{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ and ${}^{*}\!\mathbf{Br}^{\bullet}_{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ are used.
Definition 3.8. ➺ A degree $-1$ differential for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ is a family of morphisms $\{d_{n}:T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}\rightarrow T(\overline{V})_{n-1}^{% \rightarrow}\}_{n>0},$ satisfying $d_{n-1}\circ d_{n}=0\quad\forall\>n>1.$ ➺ A bidegree $-1$ bidifferential for $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$ consists of two families of morphisms $\{d_{n},d^{\prime}_{n}:T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}\rightarrow T(% \overline{V})_{n-1}^{\rightarrow}\}_{n>0},$ satisfying $d_{n-1}\circ d_{n}=d^{\prime}_{n-1}\circ d^{\prime}_{n}=d^{\prime}_{n-1}\circ d% _{n}+d_{n-1}\circ d^{\prime}_{n}=0\qquad\forall\;n>1.$ ➺ These notions allow versions “with coefficients”: one simply works on $M\otimes T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}\otimes N$ (with some objects $M$ and $N$) instead of $T(\overline{V})_{n}^{\rightarrow}.$ ➺ A collection of objects $(X_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with morphisms $(d_{n}:X_{n}\rightarrow X_{n-1})_{n>0}$ and, eventually, $(d^{\prime}_{n}:X_{n}\rightarrow X_{n-1})_{n>0}$ satisfying the conditions above is called a differential (bi)complex. Morphisms between differential complexes $(X_{n},d_{n})$ and $(Y_{n},b_{n})$ are collections of morphisms $(f_{n}:X_{n}\rightarrow Y_{n})_{n\geqslant 0}$ such that $b_{n}\circ f_{n}=f_{n-1}\circ d_{n}\qquad\forall n\geqslant 1,$ and similarly for differential bicomplexes.
Definition 2.7. A right (= left) multi-braided $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$-module structure on $\mathbf{I}$ is called a multi-braided character, or just a braided character in the rank $1$ case.
Definition 4.1. ➺ Denote by $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ the category of ✓ $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ endowed with distinguished morphisms $\overline{\nu}:=(\nu_{i}:\mathbf{I}\rightarrow V_{i})_{1\leqslant i\leqslant r}$ called units, and ✓ morphisms from $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}(\mathcal{C})$ preserving all the units. Objects $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma},\overline{\nu})$ of $\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ are called rank $r$ pointed braided systems. ➺ In the rank $1$ case, notation $\mathbf{Br}^{\bullet}(\mathcal{C})$ is used. ➺ A right multi-braided module over $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma},\overline{\nu})\in\mathbf{BrSyst}_{r}^{\bullet% }(\mathcal{C})$ is a right multi-braided $(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma})$-module $(M,\overline{\rho})$ satisfying moreover $\rho_{i}\circ(\operatorname{Id}_{M}\otimes\nu_{i})=\operatorname{Id}_{M}\;% \forall\>1\leqslant i\leqslant r$ (morally, “the units act by identity”). The category of such modules and their morphisms is denoted by $\mathbf{Mod}_{(\overline{V},\overline{\sigma},\overline{\nu})}.$ Similar definitions and notations are assumed for left modules.
Definition 5.1. (Drinfeld) Let $R$ be a commutative ring. An elementary Tate $R$-module is a topological $R$-module which is isomorphic to $P\oplus Q^{*}$, where $P,Q$ are discrete projective $R$-modules, and $Q^{*}={\mathrm{Hom}}(Q,R)$ with the natural topology4The basis of open neighborhoods of $0\in Q^{*}$ consists of annihilators of finite subsets in $Q$.. A Tate $R$-module is a topological $R$-module which is a topological direct summand of an elementary Tate $R$-module.
Definition 3.1. Let ${\mathfrak{m}}$ and ${\mathfrak{p}}$ be a group functors from the category ${\mathbf{Aff}}$ given by ${\mathfrak{m}}(R)=\left\{f\mid f\in u\cdot R[[u]]+t\cdot R((u))[[t]]\right\}$ ${\mathfrak{p}}(R)=\left\{f\mid f\in u^{-1}\cdot R[u^{-1}]+t^{-1}\cdot R((u))[t% ^{-1}]\mbox{ is nilpotent }\right\}$ with the usual addition, where $R$ is any commutative ring.
Definition 3.3. The two-dimensional Contou-Carrère symbol $(\cdot,\cdot,\cdot)$ is the unique tri-multiplicative, anti-symmetric map from ${L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}}_{\mathbf{Q}}\times{L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}}_{\mathbf{Q}}% \times{L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}}_{\mathbf{Q}}$ to ${{\mathbb{G}}_{m}}_{\mathbf{Q}}$ such that for any $\mathbf{Q}$-algebra $R$, and $f,g,h\in L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}(R)$, $(f,g,h)=\exp{\operatorname{Res}}(\log f\cdot\frac{dg}{g}\wedge\frac{dh}{h})\;% \mbox{when}\;(\nu_{1},\nu_{2})(f)=(0,0)\mbox{,}\;f_{0}=1\;(\mbox{see}~{}\eqref% {decomp2})\mbox{,}$ $(a,g,h)=a^{\nu(g,h)}\quad\mbox{when}\quad a\in R^{*}\mbox{,}$ $(f,g,h)=(-1)^{A}\quad\mbox{when}\quad f=u^{j_{1}}t^{i_{1}}\mbox{,}\quad g=u^{j% _{2}}t^{i_{2}}\mbox{,}\quad h=u^{j_{3}}t^{i_{3}}\mbox{,}$ where $A=\nu(f,g)\nu(f,h)+\nu(g,h)\nu(g,f)+\nu(h,f)\nu(h,g)+\nu(f,g)\nu(f,h)\nu(g,h)% \mbox{.}$ Here we set $df=\frac{\partial f}{\partial u}du+\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}dt$, $df\wedge dg=(\frac{\partial f}{\partial u}\frac{\partial g}{\partial t}-\frac{% \partial g}{\partial u}\frac{\partial g}{\partial t})du\wedge dt$, and ${\operatorname{Res}}\,(\sum a_{i,j}u^{j}t^{i}du\wedge dt)=a_{-1,-1}\mbox{.}$
Definition 5.2. A lattice ${\mathbb{L}}\subset R((u))((t))$ is an $R$-submodule such that there exists some $N\gg 0$ with the properties: $t^{N}R((u))[[t]]\subset{\mathbb{L}}\subset t^{-N}R((u))[[t]]$ and $t^{-N}R((u))[[t]]/{\mathbb{L}}$ (with the induced topology) is a Tate $R$-module.
Definition 3.2. We denote by $\mathcal{B}$ the full subcategory of the category of commutative rings consisting of those $R$ such that ${\mathcal{N}}R\quad\mbox{is a nilpotent ideal in}\quad R\mbox{.}$
Definition 3.4 (Explicit formula). Let $R\in\mathcal{B}$. Let $f,g,h\in L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}(R)$. Let $f=f_{0}\cdot u^{\nu_{2}(f)}t^{\nu_{1}(f)}\cdot\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2% }\setminus(0,0)}(1-a_{i,j}u^{j}t^{i})\mbox{, where}\quad f_{0}\in R^{*}\mbox{,}\quad a_{i,j}\in R\mbox{,}$ $g=g_{0}\cdot u^{\nu_{2}(g)}t^{\nu_{1}(g)}\cdot\prod_{(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2% }\setminus(0,0)}(1-b_{k,l}u^{l}t^{k})\mbox{, where}\quad g_{0}\in R^{*}\mbox{,}\quad b_{k,l}\in R\mbox{,}$ $h=h_{0}\cdot u^{\nu_{2}(h)}t^{\nu_{1}(h)}\cdot\prod_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2% }\setminus(0,0)}(1-c_{m,n}u^{n}t^{m})\mbox{, where}\quad h_{0}\in R^{*}\mbox{,}\quad c_{m,n}\in R\mbox{,}$ then the two-dimensional Contou-Carrère symbol from $L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}(R)\times L^{2}{\mathbb{G}}_{m}(R)\times L^{2}{\mathbb{G}% }_{m}(R)$ to $R^{*}$ is given as $\displaystyle(f,g,h)=(-1)^{A}f_{0}^{\nu(g,h)}g_{0}^{\nu(h,f)}h_{0}^{\nu(f,g)}% \cdot\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}\limits_% {(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}\limits_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}% \setminus(0,0)}T(a_{i,j},b_{k,l},c_{m,n})\ \times\\ \displaystyle\times\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(% 0,0)}}\limits_{(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}S(a_{i,j},b_{k,l})^{% \nu_{1}(h)}\ \cdot\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0% ,0)}}\limits_{(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}Q(a_{i,j},b_{k,l})^{% \nu_{2}(h)}\ \times\\ \displaystyle\times\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(% 0,0)}}\limits_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}S(c_{m,n},a_{i,j})^{% \nu_{1}(g)}\ \cdot\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(i,j)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0% ,0)}}\limits_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}Q(c_{m,n},a_{i,j})^{% \nu_{2}(g)}\ \times\\ \displaystyle\times\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(% 0,0)}}\limits_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}S(b_{k,l},c_{m,n})^{% \nu_{1}(f)}\ \cdot\mathop{\mathop{\prod_{(k,l)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0% ,0)}}\limits_{(m,n)\in{{\mathbf{Z}}}^{2}\setminus(0,0)}}Q(b_{k,l},c_{m,n})^{% \nu_{2}(f)}\ \mbox{,}\\ $ where $A\in\mathbb{Z}(R)$ is given by formula (3.19).
Definition 1 Let $L_{(a,b)}$, where $a$ is a substring of “$\mathrm{wec}$” and $b$ a substring of “$\vee\wedge{}^{\prime}$”, denote the language with structure rules from $a$ and signature obtained from $(0,1)$ by expansion with the elements of $b$.
Definition 3 For each of our cube categories $\mathbb{C}$, we write $[n]$ for the object representing a context of $n$ variables, and we write $\square^{n}$ for the image of $[n]$ under the Yoneda embedding $\operatorname{y}:\mathbb{C}\hookrightarrow\widehat{\mathbb{C}}$.
Definition 2 With $(a,b)$ as in Def. 1, and $T$ a theory in the language $L_{(a,b)}$, let $\mathbb{C}_{(a,b)}(T)$ denote the syntactic category of the theory $T$. We write $\mathbb{C}_{(a,b)}$ for short for $\mathbb{C}_{(a,b)}(\mathrm{Th}([0,1]))$ for the syntactic category of the topological interval with respect to the monoidal language $L_{(a,b)}$.
